issue.title: ONNX Runtime performing worse than PyTorch on BERT CPU Inference

labels.name: model:transformer
labels.description: issues related to a transformer model: BERT, GPT2, Hugging Face, Longformer, T5, etc.

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**

I run this [notebook](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/notebooks/PyTorch_Bert-Squad_OnnxRuntime_CPU.ipynb) on my machine and I can not replicate the performance improvement results.

**System information**
Macbook Pro:
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): 2.6 GHz 6-Core Intel Core i7 
EC2 Instance:
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04):  Intel(R) Xeon(R) Platinum 8175M CPU @ 2.50GHz
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.3.0
- Python version: 3.6.8

**To Reproduce**
- Run this notebook https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/notebooks/PyTorch_Bert-Squad_OnnxRuntime_CPU.ipynb

**Expected behavior**
I expected results similar to the ones cached in the notebook:

* PyTorch : `198.99 ms` 
* ONNX : `176.96 ms`
* ONNX best model after grid search: `84.73 ms` (with `OMP_NUM_THREAD = 12`, `intra_num_threads = 1`)
* ONNX worse model: `306.75 ms`   (with `OMP_NUM_THREAD = 1`, `intra_num_threads = 1`)


But on my Mac I got:
* PyTorch : `106.82 ms` 
* ONNX : `265.84 ms`
* ONNX best model after grid search: `234.48 ms` (with `OMP_NUM_THREAD = 12`, `intra_num_threads = 1`)
* ONNX worse model: `273.45 ms`  (with `OMP_NUM_THREAD = 1`, `intra_num_threads = 1`)

 

And on EC2 :
* PyTorch : `137.08 ms` 
* ONNX : `189.88 ms`
* ONNX best model after grid search: `175.70 ms` (with `OMP_NUM_THREAD = 4`, `intra_num_threads = 1`)
* ONNX worse model: `267.25 ms`  (with `OMP_NUM_THREAD = 1`, `intra_num_threads = 1`)

Thanks in advance!

cc: @tianleiwu

repository.name: onnxruntime

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
From time to time the whole JVM crashes with a thread error during Onnx utilization. It simply terminates, only a short notice in the console:
`libgomp: Thread creation failed: Resource temporarily unavailable`

Unfortunately I can not provide a test here. I use a "simple" network for object detection with standard tensors. The machine running on is a 32 core CPU system.
Before posting lot of environment stuff here please ask me what should be helpful to follow up.

Right now I am testing some setting by limiting OMP threads like this, will inform here how it works:
export MAGICK_THREAD_LIMIT=4
export OMP_NUM_THREADS=4

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): openSUSE Leap 15.2, 5.3.18-lp152.50-preempt, x86_64
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): com.microsoft.onnxruntime from Maven
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.5.2
- Python version: n/a
- GPU model and memory: n/a (CPU only)
- Java: OpenJDK Runtime Environment Zulu15.28+51-CA

body: In my Macbook, `brew uninstall libomp` vs `brew install libomp` do not observe speed difference.
Increasing the cpu cores accelerates the speed a lot in Spark cluster.  But still 4x slower than Macbook.
Java code `System.load` the `libgomp.so.1` or Not, do not observe speed difference.

What's the CPU in the server, what's the CPU in the Macbook? What settings are you using on the `OrtSession` in both cases?

Standing up a spark instance inside the same JVM might be causing a bunch of gc pressure and other nonsense that slows down the computation. Are you doing the same thing on your Macbook?

Admittedly it shouldn't slow it down by this much, so there's something else going on, but it's best to run down the differences first.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4702353/101423977-2616a400-3935-11eb-9696-db048dc57c5e.png)

The CPU in the server is better than the Macbook.

> Increasing the cpu cores accelerates the speed a lot in Spark cluster. But still 4x slower than Macbook.

This experiments' code: 
```
val df = loadData(hiveContext).limit(1)

df.repartition(1).map(row=>{
      ScoreMNIST.main(null)
      (1)
    }).show()
```
The computation is in worker of Spark.
So I installed Onnx successfully?

> ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4702353/101423977-2616a400-3935-11eb-9696-db048dc57c5e.png)
> 
> The CPU in the server is better than the Macbook.

Is it faster in a single thread? Does it have AVX-512?



> > Increasing the cpu cores accelerates the speed a lot in Spark cluster. But still 4x slower than Macbook.
> 
> This experiments' code:
> 
> ```
> val df = loadData(hiveContext).limit(1)
> 
> df.repartition(1).map(row=>{
>       ScoreMNIST.main(null)
>       (1)
>     }).show()
> ```
> 
> The computation is in worker of Spark.

So the computation happens on the spark workers or in the head node? If in the workers what resources in terms of RAM and cpu cores are assigned to the workers?

> So I installed Onnx successfully?

It's not installed, the Java version is self contained in the jar that you download from maven central (apart from libgomp, and the c standard library).

>So the computation happens on the spark workers or in the head node? If in the workers what resources in terms of RAM and cpu cores are assigned to the workers?

I try both. In worker is faster. The worker has 16-cores-CPU and 32G-memory

The Macbook's info:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4702353/101426990-02555d00-3939-11eb-9b68-dd5c368b8a61.png)

So this jar contains all the things that Onnx need to run?
```
         <dependency>
            <groupId>com.microsoft.onnxruntime</groupId>
            <artifactId>onnxruntime</artifactId>
            <version>1.5.2</version>
        </dependency>
```

> Is it faster in a single thread? Does it have AVX-512?

I will check it.
Maybe it is fast enough, I will compare the speed against without-Onnx.

> So this jar contains all the things that Onnx need to run?
> 
> ```
>          <dependency>
>             <groupId>com.microsoft.onnxruntime</groupId>
>             <artifactId>onnxruntime</artifactId>
>             <version>1.5.2</version>
>         </dependency>
> ```

Yes, that contains everything needed to run ONNX Runtime on macOS, Linux and Windows x86_64 platforms, using the CPU provider for inference (apart from libgomp, which I'm not clear if the maven central jars are compiled to use). If you want to use a different provider like dnnl or OpenVINO you'll need to compile it from source. The GPU jar supports the CUDA provider and the CPU provider.

> apart from libgomp, which I'm not clear if the maven central jars are compiled to use

I am not sure I understand this sentence. Thank you.

> > apart from libgomp, which I'm not clear if the maven central jars are compiled to use
> 
> I am not sure I understand this sentence. Thank you.

I'm not involved in the packaging of the jars for Maven Central, so I don't know what compiler flags are used. So I don't know if OpenMP is turned on in them. I think it's changed over time.

So the jar do not contain libgomp. 

Without libgomp, the jar may not work in 100% speed?

> So the jar do not contain libgomp.
> 
> Without libgomp, the jar may not work in 100% speed?

I believe there are some alternative parallelisation mechanisms other than OpenMP, but I don't know what the performance of them is vs OpenMP.
Could you please just tell me how to turn on OpenMP in my CentOS Linux server? Thank you!

The readme said:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4702353/101430968-02f1f180-3941-11eb-988c-24ac81be72a6.png)

So I use java code `System.load` to load the libgomp. I think it does not mean that I have turned on OpenMP.

Looks like the Java packaging pipeline (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/tools/ci_build/github/azure-pipelines/java-api-packaging-pipelines.yml#L30) does turn on OpenMP. I think using System.load to load OpenMP should turn it on, but given how low level a library it is, I'm not sure if that's sufficient (I'm mainly a Java programmer, not a dynamic loading expert). You can add it to the local library path and have it be dynamically loaded when ONNX Runtime is.

Either way, if you're using the demo MNIST model I'd be surprised if the lack of OpenMP was sufficient to slow down inference that much. I've demoed it on 4 core machines and it's much much faster than 0.25s per MNIST image. What model and data are you using?
